ctised religions—Islam, Christianity, Hinduism, Buddhism, North American Native spiritual belief, Judaism, popular Chinese religious practice and Bahá’í. The authors of each article pay special attention to religious moral codes of conduct governing parental behaviour, child-rearing norms and the role of children in spiritual practice. They pinpoint where positive support is provided, but also where the religions criticize or disagree with the ideas of the Convention. When considered in relation to the UN Convention, these ideas provoke a lively discussion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild rearingxReligious aspects. 0aChildren's rights. 0aFamiliesxReligious life. 4aFamily & Relationships: Child Abuse. 4aReligion. 7aLAW / Family Law / Children.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Terence R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoward, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoward, Harold, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGross, Rita M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatcher, John S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Elizabeth Lominska, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraemer, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLababidy, Leila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNarayanan, Vasudha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSewid-Smith, Daisy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruytert